{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475163"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:30:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:30:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12550"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12550"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.2,0.25,0.12,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5049"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39031"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5049"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12550"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23360"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"8150"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48776"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39031"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old girl is brought to the Emergency Department with sudden onset abdominal pain and difficulty breathing. She feels nauseated but has not vomited. She has had four previous similar episodes that have been milder. One such attack occurred after a dental appointment. She has a family history of similar episodes. She has no family history of urticaria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 118/78 mmHg, pulse 82/min, temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 22/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 98% on room air. There is swelling around her lips and eyes. She is given an initial dose adrenaline, with little immediate improvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome investigations are performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be found?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased C1 inhibitor","Increased histamine","Increased mast cells","Increased C1 inhibitor","Decreased platelet count"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture described in the stem would fit well for a diagnosis of hereditary angioedema. This condition is characterised by recurrent swelling of the limbs, trunk, face and genitals without the presence of urticaria. Typically, it takes around 24 hours to reach its peak and resolves over 48-72 hours. Notably, this condition does not cause itching or exhibit pitting. Visceral swelling in the gastrointestinal tract can lead to symptoms such as abdominal pain, vomiting and hypotension. The most severe manifestation is laryngeal swelling, which can result in fatal asphyxiation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHereditary angioedema occurs as a consequence of deficiency of C1 inhibitor (type 1), leading to increased bradykinin levels and the activation of the complement system, resulting in vasodilation, swelling and pain. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease in C1 inhibitor \u003C/strong\u003Elevels would decrease bradykinin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile allergic causes for isolated angioedema are rare, they should be considered if short-lived swelling episodes occur under similar circumstances, such as after consuming specific foods or medications. Allergies to foods or drugs typically induce hives (urticaria) and itching, along with angioedema, due to an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease in mast cells\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esubsequent histamine release\u003C/strong\u003E. However, the absence of improvement with adrenaline administration and the lack of a family history of urticaria or itching suggest that histamine and mast cell activity are not the cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s platelet count falls within the normal range in the case of hereditary angioedema. \u003Cstrong\u003EThrombocytopenia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by symptoms such as easy bruising, abnormal bleeding (such as nosebleeds, gum bleeding, melaena, petechiae), and persistent bleeding from cuts, none of which are observed in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hereditary angioedema is an autosomal dominant condition due to decreased C1 inhibitor"],"references":["Busse PJ, Christiansen SC. Hereditary Angioedema. N Engl J Med. 2020 Mar 19;382(12):1136-1148. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra1808012. PMID: 32187470."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23360"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12550"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/23360"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-08-22T08:59:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T16:11:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5049"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39031"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags